{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17616619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17616619"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:05:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:05:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16409"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16409"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.16,0.79,0.05,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9100"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74991"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9100"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16409"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60497"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4838"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5402"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21610"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21613"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25881"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74991","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74991"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously fit and healthy 63-year-old man is admitted with a 24 hour history of lower abdominal pain. He does not smoke, drinks about three glasses of wine at weekends and does not use any medications. He is found to have peritonitis due to perforated diverticular disease. An emergency bowel resection is performed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe makes good post-operative progress, but on day 4 becomes confused and disorientated. He is reviewed by the intern, who considers the possible explanations for his delirium. In general terms, medications are the most common cause of delirium. In this case, the patient\u0027s blood pressure is 118/65 mmHg, pulse 90/min and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. The breath sounds at the right base are reduced. His abdomen is soft and the wound looks healthy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most common cause of delirium after medications?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Drug or alcohol withdrawal","Post-operative state","Infection","Cerebrovascular event","Environmental changes"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDelirium is an acute confusional state characterised by disturbed consciousness, cognitive function or perception that has a fluctuating course. While medications (particularly anticholinergics, benzodiazepines, and opioids) are the most common precipitating factor, \u003Cstrong\u003Einfection\u003C/strong\u003E is the next most frequent cause. In this case, the patient\u0027s vital signs and examination findings suggest pneumonia as the likely precipitant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrug or alcohol withdrawal\u003C/strong\u003E can certainly cause delirium (particularly delirium tremens in alcohol withdrawal), but this is less common than infection in the general hospital population. In this particular case, the patient\u0027s alcohol consumption is not excessive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epost-operative state\u003C/strong\u003E is a significant risk factor for delirium, particularly in elderly patients. However, it accounts for fewer cases than infection across all hospital admissions. In this case, it would most likely occur in the period immediately after the procedure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECerebrovascular events\u003C/strong\u003E such as stroke can present with or be complicated by delirium, but are not as common a cause as infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnvironmental changes\u003C/strong\u003E such as unfamiliar surroundings, sensory deprivation, or sleep disruption can contribute to delirium but are usually considered perpetuating rather than primary precipitating factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of delirium involves identifying and treating the underlying cause (in this case, likely pneumonia), while providing supportive care including maintaining orientation, ensuring adequate hydration, and avoiding medications that may worsen confusion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Delirium is a multifactorial condition with infection being the most common precipitating factor after medications.","Early recognition and treatment of underlying causes is essential in managing delirium.","Environmental factors can both precipitate and perpetuate delirium."],"references":["Pisani MA, D\u0027Ambrosio C. Sleep and Delirium in Adults Who Are Critically Ill: A Contemporary Review. Chest. 2020 Apr;157(4):977-984. doi: 10.1016/j.chest.2019.12.003. Epub 2019 Dec 23. PMID: 31874132","Wilson JE, Mart MF, Cunningham C, Shehabi Y, Girard TD, MacLullich AMJ, Slooter AJC, Ely EW. Delirium. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2020 Nov 12;6(1):90. doi: 10.1038/s41572-020-00223-4. Erratum in: Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2020 Dec 1;6(1):94. doi: 10.1038/s41572-020-00236-z. PMID: 33184265; PMCID: PMC9012267","Wilson JE, Mart MF, Cunningham C, Shehabi Y, Girard TD, MacLullich AMJ, Slooter AJC, Ely EW. Delirium. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2020 Nov 12;6(1):90. doi: 10.1038/s41572-020-00223-4. Erratum in: Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2020 Dec 1;6(1):94. doi: 10.1038/s41572-020-00236-z. PMID: 33184265; PMCID: PMC9012267","Fong TG, Tulebaev SR, Inouye SK. Delirium in elderly adults: diagnosis, prevention and treatment. Nat Rev Neurol. 2009 Apr;5(4):210-20. doi: 10.1038/nrneurol.2009.24. PMID: 19347026; PMCID: PMC3065676."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60497"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16409"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60497","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60497"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T17:19:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T17:20:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9100"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74991"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":